node.text: One easy way to keep your pantry organized? By adding as much dedicated storage as possible. Sure, shelves are great, but go the extra mile by adding baskets and canisters to stash specific items in, then give everything in your pantry it's own dedicated space. Rather than putting stickers on each container, designate zones (for oils, condiments, snacks) with bookplates. "They keep everything organized and add vintage charm," says @lornaaragon, our home editor. Using inexpensive crates, which allow for air flow, to store potatoes and onions extends their shelf-life, while putting your prettiest bowls to good use. Learn more in our September issue or at the link in bio. 📷: @ryanliebe

node.text: If you’re hosting your last summer gathering this Labor Day weekend, we’ve got a recipe that guests will love. While you could certainly grill your ribs, our recipe for Tuscan ribs puts the oven to good use. Three racks of baby back ribs marinate with olive oil, paprika, fennel seeds, sage, thyme, and rosemary. They slow-roast in the oven for two hours until the meat is fork-tender and releases its juicy flavor. Get the recipe at the link in bio! 📷: @ryanliebe

node.text: Consider this another great reason to go apple-picking this September—or a fun and unexpected twist to serve on Rosh Hashanah, as it's Jewish custom to eat apple slices dipped in honey to ensure the new year will be fruitful and sweet. node.text: Few have seen the aging landscape change more than Boomers, those currently between the ages of 57 and 75. They were born into an era when Clairol was asking, "Does she or doesn't she?" about gray hair coverage. Plus, the dawn of science-backed skin care wouldn't break until decades later, in the late '90s and early 2000s. According to Paula's Choice founder Paula Begoun, our understanding of skin physiology was practically nonexistent in the decades prior, and it wasn't even close to the data that we have today. "You can compare it to a rotary-dial telephone and your cell phone," she says. So how did anti-aging turn into aging well? We dive in to the beauty industry’s evolution over the decades - visit the link in bio to learn more! 👆🏼

node.text: “For years, I have been an avid fan of restoration and renovation,” says @marthastewart48 in our September issue. When Martha updated a kitchen on her farm this summer, she opted for a few impactful changes over a gut renovation. “The new kitchen is both beautiful and functional, and I love that I was able to reuse the old cabinetry with just a few additions, which was both economical and easier to accomplish. It took about a month and a half to complete, and cost a fraction of what it would had I gutted the place.” She prefers open shelving because items are easy to see and access. Here, she lined the hallway between the kitchen and library with deep shelves for her yellowware. Check out the full kitchen tour in our September issue or at the link in bio. 📷: @paolaandmurray
